  <section class="sec">
    <p class="sl">Local knowledge</p>
    <h2>Mount Martha — Elevated Hillside, Sea-Change Homes, Cold Bass Strait Southerlies, Weekend & Permanent Mix</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Mount Martha is a prestigious Mornington Peninsula suburb occupying the elevated hillside above the southern shore of Port Phillip Bay, developed from the 1950s through the present as one of Melbourne's most sought-after sea-change and weekender destinations. The suburb's housing stock is diverse: the original beach cottages and postwar holiday houses in the lower streets have in many cases been replaced or renovated into substantial permanent homes, while the elevated streets on the ridge and hillside are characterised by large architect-designed homes on generous bush blocks. A high proportion of Mount Martha homes include fireplaces or slow combustion wood heaters — partly because the elevated hillside position creates a genuine cold pattern with sharp Bass Strait southerlies pushing up from the bay in winter, and partly because the peninsula lifestyle and character of the homes lends itself to wood heating as a centrepiece. The mix of permanent residents who use their fireplaces through every winter and weekender owners who visit through the cooler months creates the same intermittent-use risk pattern found throughout the peninsula: a fireplace lit after months of dormancy can have bird nests, debris and dried creosote that creates a fire risk on first use. We service Mount Martha and the surrounding peninsula suburbs regularly.</p></div>
  </section>

